Dr William Bry says the 'paired donations' are occurring thanks to a woman who started a chain of donations and a computer program that matches donors to recipients. 

Zully Broussard, 55, of Sacramento agreed to give a kidney to a man who was not compatible with his relative.

That relative, in turn, will donate a kidney to a patient who also has a family member or friend unable to donate because of compatibility issues. 

This kind of pairing continues down the line four more times until all six kidney patients get transplants, the San Francisco station reported.

The paired kidney exchange happened through computer software called MatchGrid, developed by David Jacobs, who is a kidney recipient. 

Its algorithmic program uses a person's genetic profile and finds potential matches.

Once the matches are confirmed, doctors, nurses and case managers work on the logistics of making it a reality. 

